<HEADLINE>
<P>
POSTAL PROOFREADERS MAKE ROYAL MISTAKE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Proofreaders at Canada's postal service let a royal error slip through in the 
production of a souvenir stamp book -- a reference to "the Prince of Whales." 
</P>
<P>
 Much to Canada Post's chagrin, the book was printed with a passage describing 
a visit by "the Prince of Whales" to the snowy shores in 1860.That prince 
eventually became King Edward VII, the great-great-grandfather of the present 
Prince of Wales. 
</P>
<P>
 "Unfortunately, it's just something that went through a number of people and 
got missed," Canada Post spokesman Jim Phillips said of the incorrect spelling 
of "Wales." 
</P>
<P>
 "It was a human error and there was no intended slight to the Royal Family or 
to Prince Charles." 
</P>
<P>
 He said that Canada Post will not pull the book from the shelves since the 
1994 edition is already in production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
