<HEADLINE>
<P>
METROPOLITAN DIGEST / LOS ANGELES COUNTY NEWS IN BRIEF: LOS ANGELES; 3 SCHOOLS 
GET FUNDS FOR 'TRANSPORTATION ACADEMIES' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Special "transportation academies" to prepare students to pursue careers as 
architects, engineers or urban planners will open soon at three Los Angeles 
high schools under a federal and local grant of nearly $900,000. 
</P>
<P>
 The academies will be at Locke, North Hollywood and Wilson high schools.Each 
will function as a school within a school and will enroll between 150 and 200 
students. The grant was provided by the Los Angeles County Metropolitan 
Transportation Authority and the Federal Transit Administration. 
</P>
<P>
 The goal is to provide academic and vocational training, transportation 
internships and industry mentors to students. Most of the money will be used to 
buy computer upgrades so that students can study the latest technologies 
related to transportation issues. 
</P>
<P>
 The Los Angeles Board of Education unanimously approved the grant Monday, 
praising the program for enabling schools to enter into a partnership with 
government agencies. Also, school officials said the program will allow 
students to have real-life applications of their math, geometry and other 
studies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
