<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA COUNTY REVIEW: BIOSOURCE'S WARRANTS FOR STOCK EXERCISED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JACK SEARLES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 BioSource International Inc., a Camarillo producer of immunological reagents 
and test kits used in biomedical research, reports that warrants to purchase 
700,000 shares of its common stock were exercised last month for a total price 
of $932,000. 
</P>
<P>
 James Chamberlain, president and chief executive, said the purchases mean 
"practically all" of BioSource's outstanding warrants have been exercised. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA011194-0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 003077 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
January 11, 1994, Tuesday, Valley Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Business; Page 12 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
134 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA COUNTY REVIEW: 100 WILL LOSE JOBS AS BANK BRANCHES CLOSE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JACK SEARLES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Eight Ventura County bank branches are about to be closed due to 
consolidations, throwing as many as 100 employees out of work. 
</P>
<P>
 In one of the moves, Chatsworth-based Great Western Bank will shut down 
offices of HomeFed Bank in Westlake Village, Ventura, Camarillo and Simi 
Valley.The closures will take place in February. 
</P>
<P>
 And branches of First State Bank of the Oaks in Camarillo, Simi Valley, 
Thousand Oaks and Westlake Village will be closed in April as a result of a 
takeover by First Interstate Bancorp, based in Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
 Both acquisitions were announced last year. 
</P>
<P>
 Great Western paid $151 million to the federal government's Resolution Trust 
Corp. for troubled HomeFed. 
</P>
<P>
 First Interstate, parent of First Interstate Bank, paid $23 million to a group 
that controlled Bank of the Oaks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
